<div class=3D"u-rte-resources u-fw-500">

<p>Whether you=E2=80=99re building a house or starting a new math class, a =
strong foundation is key. A solid understanding of arithmetic basics will h=
elp you not only with tonight=E2=80=99s homework, but also in feeling confi=
dent no matter where your math journey takes you next.</p>
<p>We do understand that, sometimes, half the battle is knowing where to be=
gin. That=E2=80=99s why we=E2=80=99re here to walk you through step-by-step=
.</p>
<p>After all, that=E2=80=99s kind of our thing.</p>
</div>
<div class=3D"u-rte-resources u-fw-500">
<h2>Start here: What is arithmetic?</h2>
<p>Arithmetic is the most fundamental branch of mathematics, which is why i=
t=E2=80=99s so important to learn and really understand. Arithmetic touches=
 every other branch of mathematics, acting kind of like the basic building =
blocks for more complicated and advanced topics.</p>
<p>It=E2=80=99s also a pretty broad subject. So, depending on grade level, =
arithmetic can look a little different:</p>
<ul>
<li>First &amp; second grade go through the basics of the basics: mainly <a=
 href=3D"https://photomath.com/articles/adding-integers/">addition</a> and =
<a href=3D"https://photomath.com/articles/subtracting-integers/">subtractio=
n</a>, but sometimes <a href=3D"https://photomath.com/articles/multiplying-=
integers/">multiplication</a> and <a href=3D"https://photomath.com/articles=
/dividing-integers/">division</a>, too. Second grade might also dive into r=
ounding numbers or even simple word problems.</li>
<li>Third, fourth, and fifth grade starts to get more complicated with <a h=
ref=3D"https://photomath.com/articles/fractions-how-to-divide-multiply-add-=
subtract-a-fraction/">fractions</a>, <a href=3D"https://photomath.com/artic=
les/intro-to-decimals-decimal-form-examples-and-meaning/">decimals</a>, per=
centages, proportions, and different word problems.</li>
<li>Sixth grade isn=E2=80=99t just the start of middle school (and all the =
feelings that go with it!); it can also be the end of basic arithmetic trai=
ning and the start of <a href=3D"https://photomath.com/articles/introductio=
n-to-algebra-basics-concepts-examples-practice/">algebra</a> =E2=80=94 but =
that=E2=80=99s a whole other discussion =F0=9F=98=89</li>
</ul>
<p>That being said, every school and every student is a little different, s=
o wherever you find yourself on the arithmetic adventure is totally valid!<=
/p>
<p>If you find yourself struggling with a particular example, don=E2=80=99t=
 forget to use your <a href=3D"https://photomath.com/install/">Photomath ap=
p</a> to scan the problem so we can walk you through it. For now, let=E2=80=
=99s get a good picture of arithmetic as a field of study.</p>
<h3>The formal definition of arithmetic</h3>
<p>There are a few different ways to define arithmetic as a branch of mathe=
matics, but here=E2=80=99s how we like to define it:</p>
<p><strong>Arithmetic</strong> is a branch of mathematics that deals with n=
umbers, their properties, and operations with numbers.</p>
<h3>The real-world meaning of arithmetic</h3>
<p>Sure, it=E2=80=99s nice to know the true mathematical definition of arit=
hmetic, but it=E2=80=99s also important to know how it applies to your life=
!</p>
<p>Once you start going through examples, you=E2=80=99ll see that arithmeti=
c is everywhere you look. From adding your shopping cart total to dividing =
up dinner portions, you=E2=80=99re constantly performing arithmetic whether=
 you know it or not! In a way, you can think of arithmetic as the most basi=
c everyday math.</p>
<p>Fun fact: You can also thank arithmetic for the advancement of society! =
Arithmetic has been instrumental in getting us from Ancient Egypt to now; f=
arming, economies, technology, and so much more were all made possible by a=
rithmetic. Pretty cool, right?</p>
<h2>Arithmetic basics</h2>
<p>Okay, now that we=E2=80=99ve got our bearings, let=E2=80=99s get into so=
me MATH!</p>
<p>Arithmetic is generally thought of as basic operations =E2=80=94 additio=
n, subtraction, multiplication, and division =E2=80=94 and those operations=
 are the main foundation of this branch of mathematics.</p>
<p>As you progress through arithmetic learning, those basics will combine a=
nd coexist to form other concepts like:</p>
<ul>
<li>Measuring angles</li>
<li>Calculating volume</li>
<li>Calculating area</li>
<li>Exponentiation</li>
<li>Converting units of measurement</li>
<li>Calculating percentages</li>
</ul>
<p>But right now, we=E2=80=99re focusing on the basics, so let=E2=80=99s st=
art there!</p>
<h2>Arithmetic operators</h2>
<p>Arithmetic is all about the building blocks, and the basic <a href=3D"ht=
tps://photomath.com/articles/basic-arithmetic-operations-the-four-fundament=
al-operators/">arithmetic operators</a> are some of the most important buil=
ding blocks around!</p>
<p>Operators tell us how one value should relate to another. Here are the f=
our basic arithmetic operators:</p>
